email subject: HubSpot Application Next Steps
email body: Hi Muskan, Thank you for taking the time to apply for HubSpot's Engineering team. We've reviewed your resume and think you have great qualifications. The next step in our interview process is a coding assessment. Shortly, you will receive an email with the link to our assessment but before that we want to go over a few helpful tips. You can use ANY language you want to complete the assessment. You can use ANY external libraries to help you. Allow yourself the full three hour time limit to complete the assessment to assure you're not rushed. Be sure to check out our prep guide here which outlines how the assessment is structured and evaluated. The assessment must be completed a week from today unless you request additional time. Please note that HubSpot does not permit the usage of Artificial Intelligence (AI) tools in the completion of assessments. Any questions? Let me know. Good luck! Risi

email subject: Thank You for Applying to the Software Engineering Intern at Intuitive.
email body: Hi Muskan, On behalf of the Intuitive team, we would like to thank you for your interest in our company and the time you took to apply for the Software Engineering Intern role. Your application and the associated documents will be reviewed by the University Hiring Program Team and if there is a match, a member of the team will contact you to discuss next steps. We understand that looking for an internship can be daunting and time consuming. While we canâ€™t promise that you will hear back immediately, we can promise that we will review applicants fairly and consider your qualifications throughout the entire recruiting season. We believe that setting appropriate expectations and being transparent is a good start. To that end, hereâ€™s what you can expect: Internship recruiting season at Intuitive spans through Fall, Winter and Spring. We ensure that all opportunities are posted on the career site, and every applicant is assessed against the unique relevant qualifications for each internship role. Every hiring team proceeds to interviews at different points in the recruiting season, so if you have not heard back, your application is still in consideration. While we review your application, we encourage you to visit the Careers Page and stay engaged with us by signing up for job alert and joining our Talent Community . email subject: Thank you for applying to Twilio!
email body: Hi Muskan, Thank you for your interest in a role at Twilio! We just received your application. We know that job hunting can be stressful. Our intention is to be transparent about our hiring process to help you succeed. On that note, let's talk a bit about our hiring process. Reviewing Your Application Rather than relying on bots and algorithms, Twilio has human recruiters reviewing every application, so it can take a little longer than automated screening. Also, there are no loose ends with us: we'll let you know where you stand either way. Our Interview Process If we like what we see, a recruiting team member will reach out to discuss the opportunity. The next steps could include a few rounds of interviews taking from 2-4 weeks, sometimes longer. While this email doesn't guarantee an interview, we encourage you to check out our Interview Prep Guide . Even if you don't move forward with us, it's got some great tips for active job seekers. And to get a feel for the Twilio experience, check out our culture page and follow our LinkedIn . Thanks again for your interest in building the future of communications! Thank you, -Twilio Recruiting Team #WeBuildAtTwilio

email subject: Your IBM Application: Next Steps
email body: Dear Muskan Mahajan, We are excited to see that you have applied for a position at IBM, and we want to ensure that you have the best opportunity to showcase your fantastic skills. We understand that resume alone doesn't always reflect a candidate's full potential. That's why we invite you to complete one or more of the following assessments, which will help us gain a more comprehensive view of your capabilities. IBM values accessibility and are committed to ensuring that every candidate has an equal opportunity to showcase their skills and potential. We support measures like additional time for persons with disabilities on selection assessments. We use following assessments for selection purposes. You will be invited to complete 1 or more of these assessments, depending on the role you are applying for. The next step in the process includes one or more assessments â€“ described below. The Coding Assessment - helps us to understand your level of programming knowledge and ability. You will be presented with a coding interface to solve coding challenges. This is a timed assessment. We believe that these assessments will provide you with a better opportunity to showcase your skills, and we encourage you to take them seriously. We also want to make sure that you feel comfortable and supported throughout the process. All applicants are requested to click the accommodation link below. If you are a person with a disability, please follow the link to submit any adjustments that you require, such as extra time. IBM will review the details of your requirement and work with you on any adjustment options for your application. It is important that you submit your requirements before starting any assessments. If you do not need extra time on the assessments, please mark your response in the link below. Accommodation Form Please note that this form must be completed for each position you apply for that requires an assessment. For additional information and helpful tips, please visit our blog We appreciate your interest in joining our team and wish you the best of luck as you complete these assessments. We can't wait to see all that you have to offer! Sincerely, The IBM Talent Acquisition Team 727588BR Software Engineer - Large Scale Language Models Intern: 2025

email subject: Finish next steps for your Google application
email body: Note: Please disregard if youâ€™ve completed both the Snapshot survey and coding exercise within the past 24 hours. Dear Muskan Mahajan, Thanks again for applying for the role of Software Engineering Intern, BS, Summer 2025 - United States. We sent you an email 4 days ago with links to the Snapshot survey and coding exercise. The deadline to finish these is coming up and we donâ€™t want you to miss this chance at becoming the next great Googler. Please complete both the Snapshot survey and coding exercise by 11:59pm PT on Oct 21, 2024 . We can only consider your application for this role if both are completed by the deadline. The Snapshot survey and coding exercise questions, along with your responses and your solutions, are for your eyes only . Do not forward or share them. Instructions 1. Complete the Snapshot survey : Tell us more about your skills, experience, and work preferences in a ~15-minute survey. 2. Complete the coding exercise : Give us a sense of your coding skills in this 90-minute exercise. Youâ€™ll solve two problems using your choice of C, C++, C#, Go, Java, JavaScript, or Python languages. Here are some important guidelines: Practice first : Get some practice before you start the coding exercise by clicking "Practice first" on the welcome page. We highly recommend practicing before starting the actual coding exercise. [Important] In order to access the coding exercise : Your browser needs to be logged into the same email address you were logged into that first time you accessed the coding exercise. Please also try using an incognito window in Chrome or Safari. If you are still experiencing issues, please let us know. Do not code in multiple windows : This could lead to an incorrect submission of your solutions. Be mindful of time : You have 90 minutes to complete two problems. Make sure to set aside enough time; the timer begins as soon as you click "Start timed exercise." Use research : Official documentation and standard libraries can help with structure, syntax, and/or diction. Using them is allowed and encouraged. Only submit your own work : We want to learn more about your skills, not someone elseâ€™s. Solutions or source code that come from blogs, your friends, coworkers, professors, etc., won't be reviewed. Questions or Issues? Please send an email to assessment-help@google.com, add "[Scaled Assessment]" in the subject line of your email, and include your: Name Email Address Question or description of the issue and any relevant screenshots Please report technical issues as soon as possible : We can help you with technical problems within 24 hours of starting the coding exercise, but not after. Accommodations We value inclusiveness and understand there are many ways to process information. If you require an accommodation due to a medical condition, disability, or neurodivergence, please send an email to assessment-help@google.com to request a specific accommodation or determine what options may be available. Please also add â€œ[Scaled Assessment]â€ in the subject line of your email. Let us know your accommodation needs before engaging in or completing the assessment. Accommodations include, but are not limited to: Extra time to complete the assessment Guidance on screen reader resources: Google Accessibility - built in screen reader Browser URL: https://support.google.com/accessibility/answer/7031755?hl=en#zippy=%2Cchoose-text-with-your-cursor Microsoft - Narrator Browser URL: https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/complete-guide-to-narrator-e4397a0d-ef4f-b386-d8ae-c172f109bdb1 There is no need to provide us with the nature of or reason for your request for accommodations at this time. Any information you do provide us regarding your health is provided with your explicit consent to our using such information to assess your accommodation request. You can withdraw that consent at any time by sending a subsequent email to assessment-help@google.com . Please also add â€œ[Scaled Assessment]â€ in the subject line of your email. However, if you withdraw consent before we have made an assessment we may not be able to provide you with an accommodation. Confidentiality: The information you provide in an accommodation request will only be reviewed by our global disability partner, EmployAbility, in order to assess and provide you with reasonable accommodations. Google does not require a diagnosis, treatment plan, or Government disability certificate. Thanks! Google Recruiting FAQs: Can I have an extension? To keep our process fair, we ask that everyone complete both the Snapshot survey and coding exercise by the deadline. If you have a scheduling conflict that absolutely can't be moved, let us know as soon as possible by emailing assessment-help@google.com and we're happy to talk through options. How will I know if my code is submitted? After you submit your solutions, youâ€™ll be redirected to a confirmation page that shows how many questions and lines of code you submitted as well as the language your code was submitted in. When will I get feedback about my coding exercise? Weâ€™re not able to provide any specific feedback on your coding exercise, but someone from our staffing team will be in touch after weâ€™ve had a chance to review your entire application, including your Snapshot survey and coding exercise. Please note, if you hear from someone before youâ€™ve completed the Snapshot survey and coding exercise, youâ€™ll still need to finish them by the deadline. Are there system/browser requirements to complete the survey and coding exercise? A consistent internet connection is essential for an optimal experience. We recommend testing your internet connection using our Measurement Lab tool to ensure it's stable. Please use the latest version of one of these browsers: Chrome, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Microsoft Internet Explorer, Safari. Unable to access the coding exercise? Your browser needs to be logged into the same email address you were logged into that first time you accessed the coding exercise. Please also try using an incognito window in your browser If you are still experiencing issues, please let us know. Google Inc. 1600 Amphitheatre Parkway, Mountain View, CA. 94043 You have received this email because of your recent application to Google.

email subject: Your IBM Application: Next Steps
email body: Dear Muskan Mahajan, We are excited to see that you have applied for a position at IBM, and we want to ensure that you have the best opportunity to showcase your fantastic skills. We understand that resume alone doesn't always reflect a candidate's full potential. That's why we invite you to complete one or more of the following assessments, which will help us gain a more comprehensive view of your capabilities. IBM values accessibility and are committed to ensuring that every candidate has an equal opportunity to showcase their skills and potential. We support measures like additional time for persons with disabilities on selection assessments. We use following assessments for selection purposes. You will be invited to complete 1 or more of these assessments, depending on the role you are applying for. The next step in the process includes one or more assessments â€“ described below. The Coding Assessment - helps us to understand your level of programming knowledge and ability. You will be presented with a coding interface to solve coding challenges. This is a timed assessment. We believe that these assessments will provide you with a better opportunity to showcase your skills, and we encourage you to take them seriously. We also want to make sure that you feel comfortable and supported throughout the process. All applicants are requested to click the accommodation link below. If you are a person with a disability, please follow the link to submit any adjustments that you require, such as extra time. IBM will review the details of your requirement and work with you on any adjustment options for your application. It is important that you submit your requirements before starting any assessments. If you do not need extra time on the assessments, please mark your response in the link below. Accommodation Form Please note that this form must be completed for each position you apply for that requires an assessment. For additional information and helpful tips, please visit our blog We appreciate your interest in joining our team and wish you the best of luck as you complete these assessments. We can't wait to see all that you have to offer! Sincerely, The IBM Talent Acquisition Team 729592BR Data for LLMs - Software Engineer Intern: 2025

The Snapshot survey and coding exercise questions, along with your responses and solutions, are for your eyes only . Do not forward or share them. Instructions 1. Complete the Snapshot survey : Tell us more about your skills, experience, and work preferences in a ~15-minute survey. 2. Complete the coding exercise : Give us a sense of your coding skills in this 90-minute exercise. Youâ€™ll solve two problems using your choice of C, C++, C#, Go, Java, JavaScript, or Python languages. Here are some important guidelines: Practice first : Get some practice before you start the coding exercise by clicking "Practice first" on the welcome page. We highly recommend practicing before starting the actual coding exercise. [Important] In order to access the coding exercise : Your browser needs to be logged into the same email address you were logged into that first time you accessed the coding exercise. Please also try using an incognito window in Chrome or Safari. If you are still experiencing issues, please let us know. Do not code in multiple windows : This could lead to an incorrect submission of your solutions. Be mindful of time : You have 90 minutes to complete two problems. Make sure to set aside enough time; the timer begins as soon as you click "Start timed exercise." Use research : Official documentation and standard libraries can help with structure, syntax, and/or diction. Using them is allowed and encouraged. Only submit your own work : We want to learn more about your skills, not someone elseâ€™s. Solutions or source code that come from blogs, your friends, coworkers, professors, etc., won't be reviewed. Questions or Issues? Please send an email to assessment-help@google.com, add "[Scaled Assessment]" in the subject line of your email, and include your Name Email Address Question or description of the issue and any relevant screenshots Please report technical issues as soon as possible : We can help you with technical problems within 24 hours of starting the coding exercise, but not after. Accommodations We value inclusiveness and understand there are many ways to process information. If you require an accommodation due to a medical condition, disability, or neurodivergence, please send an email to assessment-help@google.com to request a specific accommodation or determine what options may be available. Please also add â€œ[Scaled Assessment]â€ in the subject line of your email. Let us know your accommodation needs before engaging in or completing the assessment. Accommodations include, but are not limited to: Extra time to complete the assessment Guidance on screen reader resources: Google Accessibility - built in screen reader Browser URL: https://support.google.com/accessibility/answer/7031755?hl=en#zippy=%2Cchoose-text-with-your-cursor Microsoft - Narrator Browser URL: https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/complete-guide-to-narrator-e4397a0d-ef4f-b386-d8ae-c172f109bdb1 There is no need to provide us with the nature of or reason for your request for accommodations at this time. Any information you do provide us regarding your health is provided with your explicit consent to our using such information to assess your accommodation request. You can withdraw that consent at any time by sending a subsequent email to assessment-help@google.com . Please also add â€œ[Scaled Assessment]â€ in the subject line of your email. However, if you withdraw consent before we have made an assessment we may not be able to provide you with an accommodation. Confidentiality: The information you provide in an accommodation request will only be reviewed by our global disability partner, EmployAbility, in order to assess and provide you with reasonable accommodations. Google does not require a diagnosis, treatment plan, or Government disability certificate. Thanks! Google Recruiting FAQs: Can I have an extension? To keep our process fair, we ask that everyone complete both the Snapshot survey and coding exercise by the deadline. If you have a scheduling conflict that absolutely can't be moved, let us know as soon as possible by emailing assessment-help@google.com and we're happy to talk through options. How will I know if my code is submitted? After you submit your solutions, youâ€™ll be redirected to a confirmation page that shows how many questions and lines of code you submitted as well as the language your code was submitted in. When will I get feedback about my coding exercise? Weâ€™re not able to provide any specific feedback on your coding exercise, but someone from our staffing team will be in touch after weâ€™ve had a chance to review your entire application, including your Snapshot survey and coding exercise. Please note, if you hear from someone before youâ€™ve completed the Snapshot survey and coding exercise, youâ€™ll still need to finish them by the deadline. Are there system/browser requirements to complete the survey and coding exercise? A consistent internet connection is essential for an optimal experience. We recommend testing your internet connection using our Measurement Lab tool to ensure it's stable. Please use the latest version of one of these browsers: Chrome, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Microsoft Internet Explorer, Safari. Unable to access the coding exercise? Your browser needs to be logged into the same email address you were logged into that first time you accessed the coding exercise. Please also try using an incognito window in your browser If you are still experiencing issues, please let us know. Google Inc. 1600 Amphitheatre Parkway, Mountain View, CA. 94043 You have received this email because of your recent application to Google.

email subject: Harvard WECode 2025 College Conference: Tech Fellowship Application
email body: Thanks for filling out Harvard WECode 2025 College Conference: Tech Fellowship Application Here's what was received. Harvard WECode 2025 College Conference: Tech Fellowship Application Thank you for your interest! The Harvard Women Engineers Code (WECode) Conference team is hosting our annual college women in technology conference on February 15-16 , 2025 at Harvard University. We are inviting current post-secondary students who identify as women/non-binary, with a demonstrated interest in technology, to apply to our Technology Fellowship! We will select a group of WECode Technology Fellows from across the country and world. If chosen, you will be a leader in the women in tech space, partnering with our Harvard student team to publicize the LARGEST student-run women in technology conference in the world via personal social media, digital communities/networks, and local outreach, and gain leadership experience in the women in tech space. Fellows will enjoy exclusive perks, including a free ticket to the conference, networking opportunities, and access to community resources. Please review this document for more information: https://tinyurl.com/wecodetechfellows25 This application is due November 3rd, 2024 at 11:59pm EST . Additionally, we will be hosting an informational meeting on Friday, October 18th, from 7:00 to 8:00pm EST . This is a great opportunity for students to learn more about the Tech Fellow program and ask any questions they may have. Please use this link to RSVP. There are THREE PORTIONS to this application : a mandatory application for WECode Technology Fellows, a mandatory committee selection (Professional Development, Digital Media, and Peer Engagement), and an optional application for a leadership role as a lead fellow for one of the committees listed above. Short Answer Questions: What experience do you have in technology (if none, what excites you about learning it)? What are you excited to do with technology in the future? (max 250 words) Why do you want to be a WECode Tech Fellow? What will you contribute to the Fellowship? (max 250 words) If chosen, how will you publicize WECode given the 3 areas above? (max 250 words) What skills, experiences, or qualities make you a good candidate for your top choice role? (max 250 words) BY APPLYING, you agree that you have read, understood, and agreed to carry out the responsibilities described in the Technology Fellowship Details document at https://tinyurl.com/wecodetechfellows25 We look forward to your application and hope to see you at Harvard WECode! Feel free to reach out to wecodepr@gmail.com with any questions (subject with â€œTech Fellowship Programâ€ in it!) This application is only for undergraduate students. Email * muskanmahajan2004@gmail.com WECode Fellowship Application: General Technology Fellow First Name * Muskan Last Name * Mahajan Phone Number 4708367544 Pronouns This fellowship is for students of minoritized gender identities! Please reach out if you have questions. âœ“ she/her/hers they/them/theirs Other: Full Name of Post-Secondary Institution (School) -- please write the full name with appropriate capitalizations (Ex. Harvard University) * Georgia Tech City, State/Province -- please capitalize appropriately with no abbreviations! (Ex. Boston, Massachusetts) * Atlanta, Georgia Country * United States Current year in school * Must be a undergraduate post-secondary student. Enrolled students, students on gap years, and students on leaves of absences welcome! First-Year Second-Year Third-Year Fourth-Year Other: Were you a past Tech Fellow? If not, no worries! This will not impact your chance of being a Fellow for this yearâ€™s conference. * Yes No How did you find out about this opportunity? * âœ“ Instagram Facebook Slack LinkedIn Reach-out from WECode Member Friend shared with me Teacher/School Counselor Parent Group RTC Other: What experience do you have in technology (if none, what excites you about learning it)? What are you excited to do with technology in the future? (max 250 words) * My advent into technology was through developing BELA (Bot for English Language Acquisition) - a full-stack language learning chatbot for Hindi-speaking students. I built BELA using Python's NLP libraries, such as NLTK and Transformers. BELA helped 35+ underserved students at an Indian non-profit I worked at improve their English skills through constant communication and fun, bite-sized exercises. The research for this prototype was published in EMNLP 2022, a moment that reinforced my passion for technology for social good. Since then, Iâ€™ve been building web projects for my community. One example is "Affirm," a GPT-3.5-based positive affirmations generator I made using Python and Flask. It accepts a userâ€™s grievance as input and generates affirmations to help them cope better. My latest project is Buzz Bazaar, a GT-campus marketplace for second-hand goods. Since its release in May '24, it has helped 30 Yellow Jackets sell 45+ goods, make money and reduce waste. Building Buzz Bazaar taught me the value of iterative-development based on feedback and the skills to market my creation across campus. Finally, in future, I see myself develop solutions to ensure women's safety in Delhi, often dubbed India's "rape capital." This project would involve comprehensive research, leveraging the insights of survivors, policymakers, and medical professionals. My goal would be to create an accessible, frugal SOS system tailored for low-connectivity areas, empowering women with a reliable safety net that works within Indiaâ€™s unique socio-economic landscape. Why do you want to be a WECode Tech Fellow? What will you contribute to the Fellowship? (max 250 words) * A sophomore leading an interdisciplinary innovation club at her school, a senior developing an app to promote small businesses, and a junior with a tech-IG following of 25K (wink wink Skylar Basco).These are just some of the amazing women I met at Harvard WECode 2024. I want to be a WECode Tech Fellow so that I can surround myself with the incredible community of women it fosters and urge the women in my network to become a part of it too. As VP External at Georgia Tech's Women @ College of Computing club, I organize recruitment events for our network of over 650 women. Therefore, I know firsthand how impactful access to recruitment and professional development resources can be for young women in tech. Therefore, Iâ€™m eager to connect them to this unique opportunity. Finally, the professional perks of being a WECode Fellow â€” like coffee chats with companies like Notion and Five Rings LLC, and meeting other ambitious fellows across the country â€” appeal to me too. In terms of contribution, I am keen to join the Professional Development Committee. Iâ€™ve liaised with corporate sponsors like Bloomberg, Google, and Millennium in my current role at W@CC. Furthermore, as Event Director for a Womenâ€™s History Month panel discussion at "Startup Exchange" club, I have moderated discussions featuring senior leaders like Visaâ€™s SWE Director. Iâ€™m excited to emulate these at WECode, helping to facilitate impactful discussions and expand the network of mentors and speakers available to the event. If chosen, how will you publicize WECode given the 3 areas above? (max 250 words) * personal social media, digital communities/networks, and local outreach As a tech fellow for Harvard WECode, I would leverage my extensive network and leadership positions to maximize publicity for the conference. For instance, as VP External of Georgia Tech's Women at College of Computing (650+ members) and Director of Events at Startup Exchange (350+ members), I have direct access to a large pool of potential attendees. I would promote WECode through our clubs' communication channels, including dedicated posts on our opportunities board on Slack and announcements during club meetings. My role in these organizations allows me to personally endorse WECode, adding credibility to the promotion. I'd also tap into my network of fellow CS majors - honestly majority of my friends and acquaintances here at Georgia Tech - particularly focusing on ambitious women in tech who are always seeking such opportunities. Beyond campus organizations, I organize regular internship application sprintathons in my campus apartment lounge. These events provide an ideal setting to introduce WECode to a diverse group of motivated students. I would encourage all participants to apply and consider attending the conference. Lastly, I'd utilize my LinkedIn network of 1800+ followers to spread the word about WECode, reaching a broader audience of tech enthusiasts and potential attendees beyond my immediate campus community. List specific communities/platforms, if any, that you are a part of, to which you can share WECode. * e.g. coding camps, Slack groups, Facebook groups, women in tech accounts, etc. Director of Events at Startup Exchange Georgia Tech, VP External at Women at College of Computing (W@CC) at GT, Member of Girls who code, Member of SWE Social media handle(s) * Please list the handle and the according social media app muskan_mjn (my IG), waccgt (w@cc's IG), startupexchangegt (SX GT) Link(s) to resume, LinkedIn, personal websites or portfolios, anything cool really :) optional! My resume: https://drive.google.com/file/d/15TQ3ljgCNOa1tNtMr33EACkgMyUiwvIG/view?usp=sharing Linkedin: https://www.linkedin.com/in/muskanmahajan/ The web app (buzz bazaar) I created last sem: buzzbazaar.app My product hunt page: https://www.producthunt.com/products/affirm-4 By electronically signing my name below, I agree that if I am selected to be a Tech Fellow, I have read the responsibilities described in the form description and will carry them out via outreach and pubbing. I understand that not following through (not pubbing, being uncommunicative, etc.) may have my free conference ticket and other ambassador perks revoked. * Muskan Mahajan Any other comments or questions? What schools do Tech fellows represent? Also, do we have agency over organizing our own initiatives WECode Committee Selection: General Member Upon acceptance into the WECode Tech Fellowship programs, all Tech Fellows must join one of three committees and attend its meetings. Description of Committees The three committees are: [ Professional Development ] Duties include: Facilitating Tech Fellow coffee chats Sourcing professional speakers and organizing a virtual speaker series Moderating workshops on professional development. [ Digital Media ] Duties include: Writing and editing guest blog posts featured on the WECode site Lead outreach to news sources for coverage of WECode 2023 Creating content for WECodeâ€™s official social media channels (IG/Tiktok) [ Peer Engagement ] Duties include: Leading fun socials and networking events Facilitating weekly discussions on relevant topics in tech Designing Tech Fellow merch Rank the committees from in order of preference (First choice = most preferred) * Professional Development Digital Media Peer Engagement First Choice Second Choice Third Choice WECode Fellowship Application: Lead Fellows The 6 chosen Lead Fellows must complete general Technology Fellowship responsibilities, in addition to taking on the responsibility of leading the 3 committees. What role are you applying for? Please rank in order of preference (1 = most preferred). If you are only interested in one position, leave "second choice" and "third choice" blank. Professional Development Lead Fellow Digital Media Lead Fellow Peer Engagement Lead Fellow First choice Second Choice Third Choice What skills, experiences, or qualities make you a good candidate for your top choice role? (max 250 words) * I am keen to join the Professional Development Committee. As VP External at Georgia Tech's Women at College of Computing Club, Iâ€™ve liaised with corporate sponsors like Bloomberg, Google, and Millennium. This experience has equipped me with the skills to reach out and establish connections with corporates and their representatives, and organize meaningful events with them. Furthermore, as Event Director for a Womenâ€™s History Month panel discussion at "Startup Exchange" club, I have organized and moderated discussions featuring senior leaders like Visaâ€™s SWE Director and Forbes 30U30 Founder - after leading a cross functional team of 13. Iâ€™m excited to emulate this experience at WECode, helping to facilitate impactful discussions and expand the network of mentors and speakers available to the event. Any other comments or questions? email subject: Your IBM Application: Next Steps
email body: Dear Muskan Mahajan, We are excited to see that you have applied for a position at IBM, and we want to ensure that you have the best opportunity to showcase your fantastic skills. We understand that resume alone doesn't always reflect a candidate's full potential. That's why we invite you to complete one or more of the following assessments, which will help us gain a more comprehensive view of your capabilities. IBM values accessibility and are committed to ensuring that every candidate has an equal opportunity to showcase their skills and potential. We support measures like additional time for persons with disabilities on selection assessments. We use following assessments for selection purposes. You will be invited to complete 1 or more of these assessments, depending on the role you are applying for. The next step in the process includes one or more assessments â€“ described below. The Coding Assessment - helps us to understand your level of programming knowledge and ability. You will be presented with a coding interface to solve coding challenges. This is a timed assessment. We believe that these assessments will provide you with a better opportunity to showcase your skills, and we encourage you to take them seriously. We also want to make sure that you feel comfortable and supported throughout the process. All applicants are requested to click the accommodation link below. If you are a person with a disability, please follow the link to submit any adjustments that you require, such as extra time. IBM will review the details of your requirement and work with you on any adjustment options for your application. It is important that you submit your requirements before starting any assessments. If you do not need extra time on the assessments, please mark your response in the link below. Accommodation Form Please note that this form must be completed for each position you apply for that requires an assessment. For additional information and helpful tips, please visit our blog We appreciate your interest in joining our team and wish you the best of luck as you complete these assessments. We can't wait to see all that you have to offer! Sincerely, The IBM Talent Acquisition Team 727366BR Software Engineer - AI-powered Automation Intern: 2025

email subject: Blackstone Application â€“ Invitation to pymetrics Digital Interview Assessment
email body: Hello, This is a reminder that you have been invited to complete the next step of our application process where we will be leveraging the Pymetrics one-way digital interview platform. Please complete this portion of the applications process as soon as you are able. Instructions: Please click the following link to complete the pymetrics assessment: https://www.pymetrics.com/invite/sc.977b6d9a7f3d41f5a42d20f2e8e9d251/ 1. Register for a Pymetrics account (please be sure to use the same email address that you received this invitation to). 2. If using a smartphone, you will be directed to the App store. Download the app and then come back to link above. 3. Record your interview responses. Please Note: Pymetrics digital interviewing is supported on the following web browsers: Chrome, Firefox, and Microsoft Edge. On mobile, you must be on a minimum of iOS11 for Apple devices or 4.4 on Android devices. Pymetrics is not compatible with tablet devices. Next Steps: Once you have completed your interview, our recruiting team will review your responses and will be in touch with next steps. More information on the Pymetrics Digital Interview: The digital interview helps us learn more about your prior experiences and your interest in the role. This part will take an additional 20 minutes. You will be asked to record your responses to five interview questions. The video interview does not provide disability accommodations at this time. Please e-mail campusrecruiting@blackstone.com for further assistance. If you have any technical questions about completing Pymetrics, please reach out to support@pymetrics.com for help. Best, Blackstone Campus Recruiting Team Privacy Notice: Blackstone invites candidates who have applied to campus programs to submit voluntarily video recordings in which they provide answers to questions provided. The video recording will be deleted after the evaluation process has been completed, unless further storage is required by applicable law. Tips & Tricks for a Successful Video Interview DO your homework, you have a limited amount of time to convey your knowledge, research current deals and initiatives ahead of time DO treat this like an in-person interview, dress in business attire DO set up a tidy and quiet space to conduct the interview. While you are being evaluated on what you say keep in mind the reviewers can view your background DO pay attention to your lighting, avoid sitting in front of a sunlit window and try not to use overhead lighting DO test your technology ahead of time, make sure your camera, sound, and internet are all working DON'T use any examples in your answers that involve any illegal or illicit topics DON'T share the interview questions with friends or classmates, we want everyone to have an even playing field while completing DON'T read from notes, the moving of your eyes from reading can distract the reviewer. Instead, practice your answers ahead of time so you sound confident and relaxed

email subject: Blackstone Application â€“ Invitation to pymetrics Assessment
email body: Dear Muskan, As a reminder, part of your Blackstone campus program application, is completion of the pymetrics online games. We cannot further consider your application until you complete the games within the 3 day timeframe. If you do not complete the games within this timeframe, we will assume that you are no longer interested in opportunities at Blackstone and we will withdraw your application. Please note that even if you have played the 12 games already, if you have applied to multiple roles at Blackstone, you will need to release the results for every application by clicking on the unique link contained in each email you receive. If you do not click on the invite link for a role, your application for that role will not be considered complete. Best practices : - Work through the games steadily and complete in one-sitting; estimated completion timing is 25-30 minutes for all the games - Please note there are no right or wrong answers in the games; they simply give us some insights on how you would react in certain situations - Completion for the games is within 3 days of submitting your application; your application will not be complete until you complete the games Please click the following link to complete the pymetrics assessment: https://www.pymetrics.com/invite/sc.1789d38284bd43b0a1c5ff2fb8ad73c2/ Please note the following: pymetrics can be accessed on either your mobile phone or computer (please note that pymetrics cannot be played on a tablet). If you have already played pymetrics using this email address, you must still click the link above for your results to be submitted for this specific application (you will not need to replay). If you completed the games already using a different email address, please reach out to support@pymetrics.com to have your gameplay submitted for this application. If you experience technical difficulties, please contact support@pymetrics.com We hope you enjoy the games and the insights they provide. Have fun! Best, Blackstone Recruiting Team

email subject: Complete Your Netflix Software Engineering Internship Application | Next Steps
email body: Hi Muskan , Thank you for your interest in our Netflix Software Engineering Internship role! In order for your application to be reviewed, please complete this Airtable form . Your application will only be considered complete after you submit this form in conjunction with the application you already submitted on our Netflix Careers site. Please only complete the form once; duplicate submissions will not be considered. Due to the large volume of applications we receive, we're sorry that we're unable to personally follow up with each applicant. Our full recruiting process may take several weeks, so we kindly ask for your patience as we complete candidate reviews and interviews. In order to maintain a fair and equitable hiring process, we will not be able to accommodate very tight deadlines. For applicants selected to proceed, the interview process will begin with a CodeSignal Assessment. The results from this assessment will be used as just one additional data point to determine who will be invited to the interview rounds. The first two rounds of interviews are technical/coding interviews with Netflix software engineers, and the final round consists of both technical and behavioral questions. Your advancement will be based on the feedback at each round. Important Note: If you're selected to move forward, the next email you receive will come from CodeSignal; we strongly recommend adding no-reply@codesignal.com to your contacts to prevent spam filtering. Our goal is to reach out to candidates who are chosen for initial next steps within the next two to three weeks. If you havenâ€™t heard from us by then, we may have reached interview capacity. Note that our Software Engineering intern interview process is designed to assess your generalist skills, coding fundamentals, and aptitude. Offers will be extended to join our 2025 Intern class at Netflix, where weâ€™ll have 3 start date options in Summer 2025 to centralize onboarding programming and training. Thanks again, and good luck! -The Netflix Emerging Talent Team ï»¿ Please note that this email address is not monitored and replies to this message will not be read. You received this email because you've applied, been referred, attended a event, or expressed interest in working at Netflix. This email was sent to muskanmahajan2004@gmail.com by Netflix, Los Gatos,CA,USA. Unsubscribe

email body: Your students want to build a better world. And we want to help! Pramerica Life Insurance Emerging Visionaries is a national recognition program that awards student volunteers for their innovative solutions to financial and societal challenges in their communities. It is the evolution of the Pramerica Spirit of Community Awards which has honored thousands of young people during its 13-year history in India and over 27-year-old legacy in the United States. We continue to identify, celebrate and support the next generation of visionaries. Driven by Purpose. At Pramerica Life Insurance, we make lives better by solving the financial challenges of our changing world. And because we believe those solutions can come from anywhere, the more people know about Emerging Visionaries; the more impactful our work can be. So, as a progressive school that encourages students to do better for their communities and find solutions to challenges, we look forward to your participation. Help Students Apply for Pramerica Life Insurance Emerging Visionaries. Applications are open till February 18, 2024 for students of classes 8 th to 12 th . 2 national honorees will be selected to represent India at the international award ceremony in the United States* They will also qualify to receive INR 50,000 as prize money and gold medals. 23 finalists will be awarded silver medals and certificates for their dedication and commitment to their communities. Reach out to us to organise an implementation and information workshop. +91 8585 925927 # contact@emergingvisionaries.com www.emergingvisionaries.com This email was sent to muskanmahajan2004@gmail.com why did I get this? unsubscribe from this list update subscription preferences Pramerica Emerging Visionaries Â· New Delhi Â· Delhi, Delhi 110085 Â· India

email subject: [Action Advised] Jamboard application wind down
email body: The Jamboard application will be no longer be available starting October 1, 2024. Dear Jamboard user, Weâ€™re writing to let you know that we will wind down the Jamboard app next year, and offer integrations with industry-leading third-party whiteboard tools FigJam , Lucidspark , and Miro as alternatives for whiteboarding in Google Workspace. These popular tools have numerous advanced features that empower users to collaborate seamlessly together inside of Google Workspace. Starting October 1, 2024 , youâ€™ll no longer be able to create new or edit existing Jams on any platform, including the web, iOS, and Android. Between October 1, 2024 and December 31, 2024, the app will be placed in â€œview-onlyâ€ mode, during which time you can continue to back up your Jam files. Learn more . What do you need to do? Our records show that you have recently used the Jamboard app or have at least 1 Jam in your Google Drive. On December 31, 2024 , we will wind down the Jamboard application and you will no longer be able to access your Jam files. We recommend you evaluate our multiple whiteboard partners, which provide numerous advanced features that empower you to collaborate seamlessly inside of Google Workspace. FigJam by Figma Lucidspark by Lucid Software Miro In the coming months, weâ€™ll provide you paths to retain your Jamboard data or migrate it to FigJam, Lucidspark, and Miro within just a few clicks, well before the Jamboard app winds down in late 2024. Weâ€™re here to help For more information, you can visit our FAQ page . Thanks for choosing Google Workspace. â€“ The Google Workspace Team Was this information helpful? Subscribe here for more Applying for a specific role? Ask yourself these 5 questions first: Kareem Abukhadra Sep 15 READ IN APP 1) Is the role actively being hired for? You want to find roles and titles that are actively being hired for, a lot. The more jobs available, the more you can apply to. And that means you can land more interviews, receive more offers, and have more freedom. 2) Do the role's responsibilities align with my past experience? Your past experience and expertise should lend themselves to the responsibilities of the role youâ€™re applying for. Although they may not line up completely, a correlation is needed. 3) Can I tailor my resume to display my competence for the role? This is the key to landing multiple offers. You want to write your resume to make it line up with the responsibilities of the role youâ€™re applying for. Again, although they may not line up completely, itâ€™s important to cater past experiences (without lying or embellishing) to include the parts most relevant to the recruiter or hiring manager. 4) Are the role's responsibilities uniform across companies? This point is key to landing multiple offers. Itâ€™ll let you apply to each job with the same resume, and increase efficiency in the application process â€” while improving your chances of landing multiple interviews. 5) Does the role allow me to drive quantifiable value for the company? When youâ€™re able to drive (and communicate that you can drive) quantifiable value for a company, your leverage in negotiation increases exponentially. Companies donâ€™t hire out of the goodness of their heart. They hire to solve a problem, or make more money. Communicating that you accomplish one or both of those missions for them, and putting a number on it is crucial. As a general rule of thumb, you want to ask for ~20% of the value youâ€™ll drive. But, as always, that number changes with leverage. Check out this post for more info on how to accomplish this. The point is thisâ€¦ Your answer needs to be "yes" to all of these questions. This'll let you apply to multiple jobs, land multiple interviews, and negotiate with higher leverage. Any questions? Reply with them! If you liked this post and want personalized coaching for your job search, why not join our accelerator Relentless? email subject: New course with Google Cloud: Understanding and Applying Text Embeddings with Vertex AI
email body: New course with Google Cloud: Understanding and Applying Text Embeddings with Vertex AI Learn the fundamentals of text embeddings Dear Muskan, Introducing a new short course made in collaboration with Google Cloud: Understanding and Applying Text Embeddings with Vertex AI . Text embeddings, which are numerical representations of text, play a significant role in various tasks involving the identification of similar items, like Google searches, online shopping recommendations, and personalized music suggestions. With this course, youâ€™ll harness the capabilities of Google Cloudâ€™s Vertex AI API to generate text embeddings for tasks like classification, outlier detection, text clustering, and semantic search. Upon finishing the course, youâ€™ll acquire the skills to: Use text embeddings to capture the meaning of sentences and paragraphs Use the ScaNN (Scalable Nearest Neighbors) library for efficient semantic search Combine text generation from an LLM with semantic search to build a question-answering system Start integrating text embeddings into LLM applications today! email subject: Mehak Mahajan - M&A Analyst Application
email body: Dear Team Junior IB, I hope you are doing well. I am Mehak, a first-year BSc Economics student at King's College London . I am writing to apply for the M&A Analyst position at Junior IB. I've included here my CV, which provides a comprehensive overview of my academic and professional background. In my first year of university, I have been fortunate to get exposure to the financial industry by securing five finance spring week offers. I have also attached a sample report I recently wrote on Johnson & Johnson's acquisition of Abiomed . It reflects my understanding of the M&A landscape and showcases my writing skills. I hope you find it informative and insightful. I have been following Junior IB's work closely, and I am impressed by the exceptional quality of your publication. The depth of analysis, industry insights, and comprehensive coverage of M&A transactions have consistently caught my attention. Joining Junior IB would provide me with an invaluable opportunity to contribute to the M&A field while learning from like-minded peers. In addition, my enthusiasm, commitment, and strong work ethic will enable me to contribute meaningfully to your team and support the publication's mission. Once again, I sincerely appreciate your time and consideration. I look forward to the possibility of joining Junior IB and contributing to your team's success! Yours sincerely, Mehak Mahajan

email subject: Reminder: 5/22 Application Deadline for 2023 Interstellar Initiative
email body: Reminder: 5/22 Application Deadline for 2023 Interstellar Initiative Boost your career with this prestigious opportunity. Dear Colleague: I'm writing to remind you that we are inviting applications for the 2023 Interstellar Initiative through Tuesday, May 22, 2023. Presented by the Japan Agency for Medical Research and Development (AMED) and the New York Academy of Sciences (NYAS), this prestigious program takes place in New York City this fall, from September 13-15th. Selected scientists will participate in the 3-day in-person workshop , with travel expenses covered by AMED. The Interstellar Initiative builds international and interdisciplinary research collaborations between Early Career Investigators (ECIs) with the end goal of addressing challenges in basic science. Guided by mentors and supported by modest funding from AMED, teams will be established to develop proposals for international funding agencies. Learn More & Apply Here are the eligibility requirements for the Interstellar Initiative: Doctoral degree awarded no earlier than 2013 and ten years or less of active research experience. An independent, tenure-track position or an equivalent title at a university, private research institution, academic medical center, or government laboratory. Proficiency in spoken and written English for the purpose of professional science communication. A background in one of the four broad categories of biomedical sciences, life sciences, physical/natural sciences, and biotechnology/analytical technology. Is the Interstellar Initiative for you? If you want to grow professionally by working with a group of exceptionally talented cross-disciplinary early-career researchers from around the globe, under the mentorship of esteemed senior scientists, then the Interstellar Initiative is for you! Apply by May 22nd I hope to see your application for this career-boosting program by May 22nd! And please share this email with your early-career colleagues who may also be interested in applying. Thank you. Sincerely, Megan Prescott, PhD Program Manager New York Academy of Sciences Questions? Feel free to reach out to us at interstellar@nyas.org . Plug into the Worldâ€™s Smartest NetworkÂ©. email subject: Closing today: Applications for PG Diploma in Applied Statistics
email body: Submit your application before the final deadline In the Postgraduate Diploma in Applied Statistics , you will learn data analytics skills, develop an ability to distill information and clearly articulate your findings. You will also establish a solid foundation in applied statistics and learn the rigorous principles that guide statistical inference. What makes the PG Diploma in Applied Statistics special? Learn with real data from large government projects: Work with open databases used in policy and decision-making in public and private sectors. Gain expertise with specialized tracks: Choose between two specializations of Official Statistics or Data Analytics depending on your interest. Learn how to analyze, visualize, and present large data sets: The programme is built around official data systems, and youâ€™ll benefit from a 360-degree view into how these systems are built and used. Interact with and learn from globally recognised faculty: You will learn from the same faculty who teach the highly rigorous campus programmes at ISI and are also regularly engaged in the training of officers of the Indian Statistical Service. Final deadline to submit your application is today. Classes are starting on 9 Mar 2023 . Submit now Have questions? email subject: Application for Consumer/Retail Analyst Role - Mehak Mahajan (Updated CV)
email body: Dear Sir/Madam, I am a first-year BSc Economics student at King's College London, and I would like to express my interest in obtaining a place as a Consumer/Retail Analyst at ODT Capital. My decision to apply for this role stems from my passion for investment and my aim to use my research skills to develop investment recommendations for a student-led investment fund. To develop the fundamentals of finance in high school, I undertook a virtual training programme by the Indian Business School, namely â€˜Trading Basicsâ€™, through which I learnt how to analyse the corporate financial statements of a company to conduct its fundamental analysis. I completed a 1-month accounting and financial planning internship to apply this knowledge practically. Here, I prepared the ratio analysis reports of 4 major fast-moving consumer goods companies, enhancing my analytical skills. I also understood how to prepare a clientâ€™s financial plan based on their financial goals, risk appetite and financial position. At university, I participated in a trading simulation, where I built an ESG portfolio that beat the S&P500 index by 25%. During the spring break, I will complete the 12-week Investment Insight Programme at the Girls Are Investors Organisation to develop my investment skills further. I am also currently preparing for the CFA Level 1 exam. I believe that my team-building skills, communication and research competency, and ability to lead initiatives will add value to the team at ODT Capital: 1. Team player: Volunteering as an Events Associate at the King's College in London Women in Business Society and a Leadership Trainer at Girls in Charge has enabled me to work as a team player and leader. I have also previously been chosen to attend Harvard University's competitive Youth Lead Change programme, where I led a team of 5 students to pitch a hypothetical social initiative on sustainable farming. 2. Communication: Leading pro-bono projects at King's Junior Consulting Group has aided my ability to follow up with my team and the client, ensuring their needs are met. Previously, I have also represented my school at various MUNs, Youth Parliaments, debate platforms, and the â€˜World Scholar Cupâ€™, where my team was chosen for the global round in Singapore. 3. Research and Writing: My interest in research and writing has led me to opportunities like working at the Sri Ram College of Commerce for their elite Research Writing Programme, writing articles as an incoming Junior Writer at King's Business review and even starting my blog, Money Mind Media, where I conduct research and publish reports on topics of socio-economic and financial importance. 4. Entrepreneurship: I have also served as the Founder and President of my school's Business Club, the first-ever student club of my school, where I single-handedly built a team of 10 students and a membership of 70+ students. Some of our events: SVIS Business Conclave (150+ participants; distributed prices worth INR 10K), Webinar on Financial Literacy for Teens (60+ students), Walk-a-Thon Fundraiser (INR 30K raised). I am attaching my CV for your perusal. Again, thank you for considering my application, and I look forward to hearing back from you. Kind regards, Mehak Mahajan

email subject: Investment Banking Internship Application - Mehak Mahajan
email body: Dear Sir/Madam, I am a first-year Economics BSc student at King's College London , and I would like to express my interest in obtaining a place as an Investment Banking Intern at Silver Mile Capital. I aspire to pursue a career in investment banking because I think it is a challenging, fascinating, and fast-growing sector that will enable me to combine my computational and analytical backgrounds while creating a meaningful, tangible impact on other actors in the economy, like small businesses, social enterprises and large corporations. In addition, Investment banking offers a fast-paced environment where there is always something new to learn, new developments that affect your work, and opportunities to interact with diverse clients, interact with bright individuals and gain exposure to high-profile transitions. I am confident that the skills and competencies I have developed throughout my studies and extracurricular activities make me a suitable candidate. As a board member or associate, my involvement in various student societies has enabled me to cultivate my teamwork and leadership skills. I am a Consultant at King's Junior Consulting, an Events Associate at the KCL Women in Business Society and a Leadership Trainer at the nationwide Girls In Charge Initiative. Simultaneously, I have volunteered for organisations like WISH charity and Udayan Care as a Fundraising Volunteer and English Language Tutor , respectively. Since high school, I have always been interested in analysing diverse financial topics and the critical M&A transactions happening globally. This interest in research and writing has led me to gain opportunities like working at the Sri Ram College of Commerce for their elite research writing programme and even starting my blog, Money Mind Media , where I publish reports on socio-economic and financial importance. Additionally, I have served as the Founder and President of my school's Business Club , the first-ever student club of my school, where I single-handedly built a team of 10 students and a membership of 70+ students . I have also gained practical knowledge and experience in the financial industry by completing two internships in accounting and financial planning and attending financial modelling boot camps, company insight events and virtual training programmes. Participating in these activities has enabled me to stay organised, manage my time, think constructively and communicate my ideas effectively. My interest in Silver Mile Capital stems from the fact that it is a specialised investment bank and the company's culture and values. After researching the company, I found out that Silver Mile puts a strong emphasis on offering employees a supportive environment where they can challenge themselves to tackle complex financial problems and make a meaningful impact. I am sure that an internship at Silver Mile Capital will offer me an excellent opportunity to gain invaluable knowledge of how investment banking operates, as well as the chance to apply my knowledge in practice and add more pieces to the puzzle of my understanding of this fascinating field. In addition, experiencing the work and culture of the company and gaining exposure to business while networking with professionals and students interested in investment banking is a great way to deepen my understanding of the sector. Therefore, I am attaching my CV for your perusal. Thank you for considering my application, and I am excited to hear from you. Kind regards, Mehak Mahajan

email body: Watch this video of Introduction to Sustainable Operations and Supply Chain The world is facing two significant problems: Climate change and loss of biodiversity . email subject: Submit your application for review by a former admissions officer!
email body: Hello! Hope you are doing well! Ben will be meeting with former MIT and Cornell admissions officer Angela Conley on October 24th and 25th to go over our students' applications for EA/ED. You just have to submit your application in time for review. The link is here: https://ivyachievement.formstack.com/forms/reviewupload Please submit by 10PM your local time on Saturday, October 22nd! (Angela needs some time to review before meeting with Ben.) You will get feedback on: 1. Academics and test scores 2. Extracurricular activities 3. Essays 4. Letters of recommendation (if available) 5. Any "red flags" identified You should upload as much as you can to simulate the real admissions process . This means a PDF of your Common App, transcripts, score reports (even if self-reporting), resume/CV (if submitting), all LORs that you have, and anything else you might be submitting to colleges. In addition to your Common App, you may submit up to two supplements . Files are stored securely. Please refer to the attached formatting and writing guide to finalize your essays and remainder of your application for submission. Pay special attention to the sections on line spacing and capitalization ; they can help you avoid common mistakes. If you don't yet have a PDF of your Common App or have made changes since your last submission, select any school you haven't applied to yet (and whose application is complete) and click " Review and Submit - Common App, " then click " Review and Submit ." Don't worry - this will not actually submit your Common App. You'll then be able to right-click on the PDF that pops up and save it to your computer. Please let us know if there's anything we can help with! The IvyAchievement Team

email subject: 5 ways to get ahead of the US application process!
email body: 5 ways to get ahead of the US application process! You are 45 days away from the first US Early Application deadline. Here are 5 things you must complete now. Dear Vikas, You are 45 days away from the first US Early Application deadline! Here are 5 things you must complete now: 1. Finalise your list of Early Action/Early Decision colleges You must identify your best-fit colleges and apply early to optimise your chances. 2. Engage with colleges on your list Attend admissions sessions, embark on virtual tours, register for interviews and connect with colleges, their faculty and alums via their social media pages. Doing so will enable you to demonstrate interest and assimilate content for supplementary essays. 3. Complete your essays for early round applications While the Common App essay gives admissions officers an insight into who you are, Supplementary essays like â€œWhy This College/Majorâ€ showcase your keenness to join a college. So, donâ€™t leave them for the last minute. Before writing them, thoroughly research the topic and colleges you wish to attend. 4. Fill out your FAFSA/CSS profile if you are applying for financial aid Check the deadlines and eligibility for financial aid and merit-based scholarships for colleges on your list and begin the application process. 5. Finalise your recommenders Speak to your school counsellor and teachers about your letters of recommendation. It is important to choose people who know you the best and can talk about your growth. Regards, Sheetal Vora Head of Undergraduate Admissions This email was sent to muskanmahajan2004@gmail.com why did I get this? unsubscribe from this list update subscription preferences The Red Pen Â· Prasad Chambers, #411 Â· Mumbai, MH 400004 Â· India

email subject: Closing today: Applications for PG Diploma in Applied Statistics from Indian Statistical Institute
email body: Build in-demand skills in applied statistics and quantitative analytics In the Postgraduate Diploma in Applied Statistics, you will learn the statistical tools and concepts necessary to make data-driven decisions. You will also develop experience with statistical data analysis tools and acquire diverse skills required for roles that handle data analytics and applied statistics. Having a bachelorâ€™s degree and fundamental knowledge of high school level mathematics are the only requirements to apply for this programme. What makes this PG Diploma special? Learn from world-class faculty: You will learn from the expert faculty who train officers of the Indian Statistical Service. Youâ€™ll also be able to clear your doubts through live sessions and emails. Learn how to manage, analyse, visualise, and present large data sets: You will acquire skills in scientific management of data to make data-driven decisions. Choose your specialisation: The programme, apart from instilling basic knowledge, also offers you a choice between two tracks - Official Statistics and Data Analytics, based on your area of interest. Real-world based learning: You will learn with real data from governments and organisations that are available in the public domain, for example, census data from the Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation. You will also explore case studies and learn to analyse data to solve real world problems. Last date to submit applcations is today. Apply now Have questions? Schedule a call with our admissions counsellor! About Indian Statistical Institute ISI functions under the Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation (MOSPI) of the Government of India and is involved in high impact projects involving large data and also trains the key officers of the ministry. ISI Kolkata has more than 250 faculty members who have achieved excellence in their research work. The contribution of the faculty has been recognized frequently with awards such as the Padma Shri Award, S. S. Bhatnagar Award, Fellowship of Indian Academy of Science to name a few. 18 scientists from ISI Kolkata got featured among the top 2% scientists in a global list compiled by the prestigious Stanford University in October 2021. email subject: Closing soon: Applications close on July 31st for the PG Diploma in Applied Statistics
email body: Submit your application by July 31st for the PG Diploma in Applied Statistics from Indian Statistical Institute In the Postgraduate Diploma in Applied Statistics, you will learn data analytics skills, develop an ability to distill information and clearly articulate your findings. You will also establish a solid foundation in applied statistics and learn the rigorous principles that guide statistical inference. What makes the PG Diploma in Applied Statistics special? Learn with real data from large government projects: Work with open databases used in policy and decision-making in public and private sectors. Gain expertise with specialized tracks: Choose between two concentrations of official statistics or data analytics depending on your interest. Learn how to analyze, visualize, and present large data sets: The programme is built around official data systems, and youâ€™ll benefit from a 360-degree view into how these systems are built and used. Interact with and learn from globally recognised faculty: You will learn from the same faculty who teach the highly rigorous campus programmes at ISI and are also regularly engaged in the training of officers of the Indian Statistical Service. Programme duration: 12 months Fees: Rs. 4,50,000 / $ 6000 Last date to submit applcations: 31 July 2022 Classes start: 28 August 2022 Start my application Have questions? email body: The deadline to apply is March 15, 2022. Need-Based Financial Aid Dear , Stanford Pre-Collegiate Summer Institutes is committed to equity and access. email subject: Your college application January to-do list (or, happy new year)
email body: Your college application January to-do list (or, happy new year) It's January, the final 6 months of your senior year. Center kindness. Dear Seniors â€“ Happy New Year! Hopefully you were able to take some time over your school vacation to rest, relax, and recover from what was likely a stressful fall before starting back to school for this final stretch. For some of you, the college application process ended with confetti and an acceptance to your Early Decision school last month. For others, the process goes on as Regular Decision (or Early Decision 2) applications are completed and submitted in the coming days and the long wait of winter begins. There are a few things that are important for you to keep in mind this winter: 1. Trust your process! Recognize and appreciate the depth of the thoughtful and careful work you have been doing all summer and fall. While this time can feel challenging as you wait and feel like your fate is at the mercy of the college admissions offices, trust that you have done your very best work on your applications, that you have created a balanced list of schools, and that this will all work out! 2. Recognize that there is still time This might feel like the opposite of the point I just made. However, as you hear back from your Early Action schools this winter (many EA programs release decisions in late January), know that you can still find some wonderful likely schools to apply to this winter! There are many, many schools out there whose application deadlines might range from January 15th to February 15th (or even later). If you are curious about which schools those might be, first check your Common App deadlines, but also check out this comprehensive list of Late Application Deadlines (from the College Board ). 3. Know that you are not alone This is a moment to be graceful and lean into kindness as your friends and classmates reconcile their hard work on applications with admissions decisions that might or might not be what they had hoped. Now more than ever is the time to â€œchoose kindâ€ in your responses, to pause before you react or respond to a college acceptance celebration Insta post, and to applaud the successes that you see. Remember, it always works out â€“ sometimes it just takes a little longer and goes on a slightly different path than you had planned. For more on this, check out this excellent blog post from the Georgia Tech Admissions Office (â€œ Applying to College is Not Like the Movies â€). 4. You only get one senior year! Seize this moment! You have about six months left in a high school career that has certainly not been the one you imagined at the beginning of 9th grade. COVID disruptions, Zoom school, socially distant proms, and canceled athletic seasons have all disrupted high school in different ways. In these last few months, seize opportunities to celebrate and make the most of this time you have left. Your high school class will never be together, fully, in this way again. Take opportunities to celebrate, be goofy, and enjoy this time together. 5. For the adults in your life, reflect on how you want to react to your child's admissions decisions Alas, it's behind a paywall, but if you have the opportunity to read this wonderful piece from Forbes â€œ Handling College Admissions Decisions: A Sidecar Parentâ€™s Guide, â€ Brennan Barnard offers some excellent (and timely) advice on how adults can and should respond as admissions decisions come in. Thatâ€™s all for now! Iâ€™ll be back on April 1 with some more information about how to interpret and respond to the decisions that you have received (including information about managing the Waitlist). All my best and happy new year! Elise Elise London Elise spent fourteen years working as a high school college counselor in highly selective independent schools. She loves the college process for the ways it asks students to begin to articulate their purpose and their passions as they take the next step in their education. email subject: Your college application December to-do list (so, here we are at last)
email body: Your college application December to-do list (so, here we are at last) It's December. Either you'll be done soon or you'll keep chugging. Chin up. Center kindness. Hello there, Well, here we are! For some of you, December marks the official end of your months of research and hard work as an admission to an Early Decision school comes around. For others, December is just another month in a thoughtful and purposeful process. It is important this month to keep your chin up. As you hear about acceptances from classmates and peers, help them to celebrate even if you are processing a deferral or a rejection yourself. Remember, there are a lot of factors that go into a college application and decision. It is impossible to know why one classmate was admitted and another rejected. Please donâ€™t make uninformed snap judgements about your peers. Remember back in August when we centered kindness? December is a wonderful time to resurface that emotion. If your college application process is continuing, here are some important tasks to complete in December: 1. Finish the supplements For many schools, January 1 is the deadline for all regular decision applications. If you are relying on the feedback of a teacher to support your writing, it is essential that you provide drafts to that teacher for comments well in advance of the winter school holiday. It is not fair to ask a teacher (or college counselor) to read and edit a supplement essay for you between Christmas and New Year. 2. Update your Common Application? You are allowed to make any edits or changes to your Common Application between submitting it in November and submitting it again to new schools in January. Do you have fall test scores to add? Have you changed your schedule? Do you have a new favorite activity? Take the time now to make sure that your Common Application is the best reflection of you that it possibly can be. 3. Consider Additional Information On the â€œWritingâ€ page of your Common App, you should notice additional, optional spaces to include more writing. Here, you have the opportunity in a very open-ended way to share more information with the schools on your list. Remember, whatever you add here will be shared with all of the schools you apply to, so do not make this a statement that is specific to any one college. That said, you have 650 additional words to support or advocate for yourself. Do you have another essay you would like to share? Does it say something meaningfully different from your main essay? Take your time to consider what, if anything, you might want to include in the Additional Information section. 4. Manage Financial Aid applications Working with your family, be sure that you are ready to submit your FAFSA and, if needed, your CSS Profile and school-specific financial aid forms to the regular decision schools on your list. Some schools might send you additional financial aid paperwork (something like a â€œFederal Verification Formâ€) or ask you to submit a â€œTax Transcriptâ€ in addition to your other paperwork. Follow the steps they indicate. If you have questions, remember that Financial Aid officers are people too, and you can always call them to make an appointment to talk this through. The FAFSA allows you to submit to only 10 schools at a time. If you have more than 10 schools on your RD list, do not worry! Submit your FAFSA to the first 10 schools. Wait 3-5 business days. Log back into your FAFSA and delete those schools (it has been sent to them now) and add the rest of your list. 5. Donâ€™t forget a â€œThank Youâ€ Your teachers worked hard to write thoughtful letters to support your college application process. Please take time in December to hand write them a thank you note. Be specific and gracious. If you feel comfortable doing so, keep them updated and in the loop as your decisions come out. At a minimum, please let them know where you are planning to matriculate! They care about you and about your success. Yes, this is a busy time, but know that you have got this! All of the careful work you have done already this year will make many of these tasks easy to complete. If you would like additional support on any of the above, please schedule a meeting with a member of the Cambridge Coaching team here . We love to make this process more manageable for students like you. All the best, Elise Elise London Elise spent fourteen years working as a high school college counselor in highly selective independent schools. She loves the college process for the ways it asks students to begin to articulate their purpose and their passions as they take the next step in their education.
